<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1548,2005]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
Despite its streak-plumaged females, New Guinean 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stresemann &amp; Paludan" authorityYear="1934" box="[764,898,1548,1573]" class="Aves" family="Pachycephalidae" genus="Rhagologus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[764,898,1548,1573]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Rhagologus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has traditionally been included in the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1831" box="[151,339,1583,1608]" class="Aves" family="Pachycephalidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Pachycephalidae</taxonomicName>
(Australasian whistlers) because of its whistler-like appearance (
<emphasis box="[1071,1104,1585,1608]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">e.g</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Salvadori, T." box="[1119,1293,1583,1608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="896 - 976" refId="ref19108" refString="Salvadori, T. (1876) Descrizione di cinquantotto nuove specie di uccelli, ed osservazioni intorno ad altre poco note, della Nuova Guinea e di altre Isole Papuane, raccolte del Dr. Odoardo Beccari e dai cacciatore del. Sig. A. A. Bruijn. Annali del Museo civico di storia naturale di Genova, 7 (56 / 61), 896 - 976." type="journal article" year="1876">Salvadori 1876</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mayr, E." box="[1305,1431,1583,1608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" refId="ref18185" refString="Mayr, E. (1941) List of New Guinea Birds. American Museum of Natural History, New York, 260 pp." type="book" year="1941">Mayr 1941</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mayr, E." box="[151,211,1620,1645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="3 - 51" refId="ref18210" refString="Mayr, E. (1967) Subfamily Pachycephalinae. In: Paynter, R. A. Jr. (Ed.), Check-list of Birds of the World, A Continuation of the Work of James L. Peters. Vol. 12. Museum of Comparative Zoology, Cambridge, Massachusetts, pp. 3 - 51." type="book chapter" year="1967">1967</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rand, A. &amp; Gilliard, E. T." box="[231,507,1620,1645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" refId="ref18830" refString="Rand, A. L &amp; Gilliard, E. T. (1967) Handbook of New Guinea Birds. Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson, London, 611 pp." type="book" year="1967">Rand &amp; Gilliard 1967</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Sibley, C. E. &amp; Monroe, B. L. Jr." box="[527,816,1620,1645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" refId="ref19862" refString="Sibley, C. E. &amp; Monroe, B. L. Jr. (1990) Distribution and Taxonomy of Birds of the World. Yale University Press, New Haven, 1111 pp." type="book" year="1990">Sibley &amp; Monroe 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dickinson, E. C." box="[837,1027,1620,1645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" refId="ref16665" refString="Dickinson, E. C. (Ed.) (2003) The Howard and Moore Complete Checklist of the Birds of the World. 3 rd Edition. Christopher Helm, London, 1039 pp." type="book" year="2003">Dickinson 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Boles, W. E." box="[1048,1201,1620,1645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="374 - 437" refId="ref15799" refString="Boles, W. E. (2007 a) Family Pachycephalidae (whistlers). In: del Hoyo, J., Elliott, A. &amp; Christie, D. (Eds.), Handbook of the Birds of the World. Vol. 12. Lynx Edicions, Barcelona, pp. 374 - 437." type="book chapter" year="2007">Boles 2007a</bibRefCitation>
). Early DNA-DNA hybridization work (
<bibRefCitation author="Sibley, C. G. &amp; Ahlquist, J. E." box="[382,658,1655,1680]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="251 - 255" refId="ref19636" refString="Sibley, C. G. &amp; Ahlquist, J. E. (1982) The relationships of the Australasian whistlers Pachycephala as indicated by DNA hybridization. Emu, 82, 251 - 255. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1071 / mu 9820199" type="journal article" year="1982">Sibley &amp; Ahlquist 1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Sibley, C. G. &amp; Ahlquist, J. E." box="[671,729,1655,1680]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref19731" refString="Sibley, C. G. &amp; Ahlquist, J. E. (1985) The phylogeny and classification of the Australo-Papuan passerine birds. Emu, 85, 1 - 14. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1071 / mu 9850001" type="journal article" year="1985">1985</bibRefCitation>
, 1990) lent support to that presumption. Nevertheless, all five multi-locus DNA sequence studies that have screened 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stresemann &amp; Paludan" authorityYear="1934" box="[762,896,1692,1717]" class="Aves" family="Pachycephalidae" genus="Rhagologus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[762,896,1692,1717]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Rhagologus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jonsson, K. A. &amp; Bowie, R. C. K. &amp; Norman, J. A. &amp; Christidis, L. &amp; Fjelds a, J." box="[910,1130,1692,1717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="71 - 74" refId="ref17586" refString="Jonsson, K. A., Bowie, R. C. K., Norman, J. A., Christidis, L. &amp; Fjelds a, J. (2007) Polyphyletic origin of toxic pitohui birds suggests widespread occurrence of toxicity in corvoid birds. Biology Letters, 4, 71 - 74. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1098 / rsbl. 2007.0464" type="journal article" year="2007">
Jønsson 
<emphasis box="[1008,1056,1692,1717]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Jonsson, K. A. &amp; Bowie, R. C. K. &amp; Nylander, J. A. A. &amp; Christidis, L. &amp; Norman, J. A. &amp; Fjeldsa, J." box="[1141,1200,1692,1717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="1767 - 1781" refId="ref17767" refString="Jonsson, K. A., Bowie, R. C. K., Nylander, J. A. A., Christidis, L., Norman, J. A. &amp; Fjeldsa, J. (2010) Biogeographical history of cuckoo-shrikes (Aves: Passeriformes): transoceanic colonization of Africa from Australo-Papua. Journal of Biogeography, 37, 1767 - 1781. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2699.2010.02328. x" type="journal article" year="2010">2010</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Jonsson, K. A. &amp; Fabre, P. - H. &amp; Ricklefs, R. E. &amp; Fjelds a, J." box="[1211,1269,1692,1717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="2328 - 2333" refId="ref17856" refString="Jonsson, K. A., Fabre, P. - H., Ricklefs, R. E. &amp; Fjelds a, J. (2011) Major global radiation of corvoid birds originated in the proto- Papuan archipelago. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA, 108, 2328 - 2333. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1073 / pnas. 1018956108" type="journal article" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Norman, J. A. &amp; Ericson, P. G. &amp; Jonsson, K. A. &amp; Fjelds a, J. &amp; Christidis, L." pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="488 - 497" refId="ref18462" refString="Norman, J. A., Ericson, P. G. P, Jonsson, K. A., Fjelds a, J. &amp; Christidis, L. (2009 b) A multi-gene phylogeny reveals novel relationships for aberrant genera of Australo-Papuan core Corvoidea and polyphyly of the Pachycephalidae and Psophodidae (Aves: Passeriformes). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 52, 488 - 497. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2009.03.019" type="journal article" year="2009">
Norman 
<emphasis box="[1380,1429,1692,1717]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">et al</emphasis>
. 2009b
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Aggerbeck, M. &amp; Fjelds a, J. &amp; Christidis, L. &amp; Fabre, P. - H. &amp; Jonsson, K. A." box="[236,490,1727,1752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="272 - 285" refId="ref15184" refString="Aggerbeck, M., Fjelds a, J., Christidis, L., Fabre, P. - H. &amp; Jonsson, K. A. (2014) Resolving deep lineage divergences in core corvoid passerine birds supports a proto-Papuan island origin. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 70, 272 - 285. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2013.09.027" type="journal article" year="2014">
Aggerbeck 
<emphasis box="[367,417,1727,1752]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
) place it firmly elsewhere, among a complex of corvoid songbirds that includes the Australasian butcherbirds and woodswallows (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vigors" authorityYear="1825" box="[719,844,1764,1789]" class="Aves" family="Artamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Artamidae</taxonomicName>
), African bush-shrikes, wattle-eyes and vangids (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1824" box="[158,329,1799,1824]" class="Aves" family="Malaconotidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Malaconotidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[345,500,1799,1824]" class="Aves" family="Platysteiridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Platysteiridae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1831" box="[516,625,1799,1824]" class="Aves" family="Vangidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Vangidae</taxonomicName>
), southeast Asian ioras (
<taxonomicName authorityName="G.R.Gray" authorityYear="1869" box="[914,1062,1799,1824]" class="Aves" family="Aegithinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Aegithinidae</taxonomicName>
) and Old World cuckoo-shrikes (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vigors" authorityYear="1825" box="[158,346,1836,1861]" class="Aves" family="Campephagidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Campephagidae</taxonomicName>
). Nearest relatives within that complex are still unclear. The ioras (
<bibRefCitation author="Jonsson, K. A. &amp; Fabre, P. - H. &amp; Ricklefs, R. E. &amp; Fjelds a, J." box="[1126,1351,1836,1861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="2328 - 2333" refId="ref17856" refString="Jonsson, K. A., Fabre, P. - H., Ricklefs, R. E. &amp; Fjelds a, J. (2011) Major global radiation of corvoid birds originated in the proto- Papuan archipelago. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA, 108, 2328 - 2333. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1073 / pnas. 1018956108" type="journal article" year="2011">
Jønsson 
<emphasis box="[1226,1278,1836,1861]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
) or the cracticid-artamid group (
<bibRefCitation author="Aggerbeck, M. &amp; Fjelds a, J. &amp; Christidis, L. &amp; Fabre, P. - H. &amp; Jonsson, K. A." box="[433,693,1871,1896]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" pagination="272 - 285" refId="ref15184" refString="Aggerbeck, M., Fjelds a, J., Christidis, L., Fabre, P. - H. &amp; Jonsson, K. A. (2014) Resolving deep lineage divergences in core corvoid passerine birds supports a proto-Papuan island origin. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 70, 272 - 285. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2013.09.027" type="journal article" year="2014">
Aggerbeck 
<emphasis box="[567,618,1871,1896]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
) have been indicated, but support values are weak, and depth of divergence considerable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1548,2005]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,151,464]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="510" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
As diagnosed, frugivorous 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stresemann &amp; Paludan" authorityYear="1934" box="[531,665,1944,1969]" class="Aves" family="Pachycephalidae" genus="Rhagologus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[531,665,1944,1969]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Rhagologus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has little in common with the insectivorous ioras, which are predominantly yellow-, green- and black-plumaged with silken-plumed flanks, display aerobatically and build perched cup-shaped nests bound smoothly with cobweb. Nor do its rather broad palate, open nares and unstructured temporal region of the skull resemble the narrowed palate, heavily ossified nasal cavity and compound zygomatic processes found in the Australasian butcherbirds and woodswallows (
<bibRefCitation author="Schodde, R. &amp; Mason, I. J." pageId="9" pageNumber="510" refId="ref19607" refString="Schodde, R. &amp; Mason, I. J. (1999) The Directory of Australian Birds Passerines. CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne, 551 pp." type="book" year="1999">Schodde &amp; Mason 1999: 533</bibRefCitation>
) and, in part, vangas. The insectivorous pachycephalids have a broad palate and internally perforate nasal cavity similar in form to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stresemann &amp; Paludan" authorityYear="1934" box="[593,727,295,320]" class="Aves" family="Pachycephalidae" genus="Rhagologus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[593,727,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Rhagologus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the temporal region of the skull differs markedly: its fossa is much narrower, deeper and more clearly defined in pachycephalids, and both postorbital and simple zygomatic processes are well-developed and directed ventrally at an angle of 
<emphasis box="[917,929,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">c</emphasis>
. 45º. Combined morphological, behavioural and DNA sequence evidence reveal 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stresemann &amp; Paludan" authorityYear="1934" box="[557,691,404,429]" class="Aves" family="Pachycephalidae" genus="Rhagologus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[557,691,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Rhagologus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a deeply divergent corvoid lineage that cannot be placed in any other family. Accordingly, it is described at family rank here.
</paragraph>
